\ip 11. Who was Elias?—\rem [it] " Elijah the propnet."\rem [it]*
\ip 12. Why was he expected to reappear? \rq (Mal. 4. 5)\rq*—\rem [it] Because Malachi prophesied that he should come.\rem [it]*
\ip 13. Who was meant by "that prophet"?—\rem [it] Christ, who, like Moses, was a mediator and teacher.\rem [it]*
\rem \q1 The Lord thy God will raise up unto thee a prophet from the midst of thee of thy brethren; like unto me. Deut. 18. 15.
\ip 14. Why did John call Jesus the "Lamb of God"?—\rem [it] Because he was the spotless sacrifice and gift of God.\rem [it]*
\ip 15. What further proof of the freeness of the gospel is there in verse 29?—\rem [it] He "taketh away the sin of the world."\rem [it]*
\ip 16. What language is the word "rabbi"?—\rem [it] Hebrew.\rem [it]*
\ip 17. In what estimation was Nazareth commonly held?—\rem [it] It was much despised— more even than Galilee in general, whose inhabitants were looked down upon by the more civilized Jews.\rem [it]*
\ip 18. Can we too often use Philip's invitation?—\rem [it] No. Having seen and known Jesus ourselves, we should say unto all who inquire, and all who doubt, and all who pass by, " Come and see."\rem [it]*
\ip 19. What is an " Israelite indeed"?—\rem [it] One who sincerely inquires or believes.\rem [it]*
\rem \q1 Truly God is good to Israel, even to such as are of a clean heart. Ps. 73. 1.
\rem \q1 For he is not a Jew, which is one outwardly; neither is that circumcision, which is outward in the flesh: but he is a Jew, which is one inwardly; and circumcision is that of the heart, in the spirit, and not in the letter: whose praise is not of men, but of God. Rom. 2. 28, 29.
