\ip 2. How must we come to the Father?—\rem [it] By Christ, the only way.\rem [it]*
\ip 3. How do we know that our Lord was a perfect manifestation of the Father?—\rem [it] By Christ's assertion to Philip that whoever had seen him had seen the Father. Vs. 7, etc.\rem [it]*
\ip 4. Who will answer our petitions? \rq (V. 14)\rq*—\rem [it] Our heavenly Father, if we ask in Jesus' name.\rem [it]*
\ip 5. Who was the promised Comforter? \rq (V. 26)\rq*—\rem [it] The Holy Ghost.\rem [it]*
\ip 6. Was the Holy Ghost a temporary gift?—\rem [it] No; to abide with us for ever.\rem [it]*
\ip 7. Why cannot the world receive him?—\rem [it] Because it knows him not, nor Christ, through whom he comes.\rem [it]*
\ip 8. How can we judge whether we love Christ? \rq (Vs. 21, 23)\rq*—\rem [it] By our prevailing obedience to his commands, by the witness of the Spirit within us that we love Him who first loved us.\rem [it]*
\ip 9. What enabled the evangelists to remember the savings and doings of the Lord? \rq (V. 26)\rq*—\rem [it] The teaching of 'the Holy Ghost.\rem [it]*
\ip 10. Did Christ mean that his disciples shall have peace on earth when he gave them his peace? \rq (John 16. 33)\rq*—\rem [it] No; he told them they should have tribulation without, but peace within.\rem [it]*
\ip 11. Who only could say with truth that he had yielded no allegiance to the prince of this world? \rq (V. 30)\rq*—\rem [it] Jesus Christ.\rem [it]*
\ip 12. Who is the prince of this world?—\rem [it] Satan, who rules over the evil spirits of the air and in the hearts of men.\rem [it]*
\ms4 John 15.
\ip 1. In what condition only can we bring forth fruit? \rq (V. 5)\rq*—\rem [it] By being united to Christ and abiding in him by a living faith.\rem [it]*
\ip 2. What will be the consequence of our not bearing fruit? \rq (V. 6)\rq*—\rem [it] Eternal misery in separation from God and Christ, as dead leaves are cast forth and burned.\rem [it]*
\ip 3. What is the token of being Christ's friends? \rq (V. 14)\rq*—\rem [it] The doing whatsoever he commands.\rem [it]*
\ip 4. Are we to be surprised by the hatred of the world?—\rem [it] No, for it first hated our Lord, who was perfect goodness and perfect love.\rem [it]*
\ip 5. Is love of the world compatible with love to our Lord? \rq (V. 19)\rq*—\rem [it] No; there can be no true love for a holy Saviour and an unholy world.\rem [it]*
\ip 6. What sin is referred to in verses 22 and 24?—\rem [it] The sin of seeing Christ's miracles and hearing his words, and yet rejecting both God and him.\rem [it]*
\ms4 John 16.
\ip 1. Compare verse 2 with Acts 26. 9-11—\rem [it]  Sau 1 thought when in his unconverted state that he ought to persecute the followers of Christ.\rem [it]*
\ip 2. What was the " little while " in verse 16?—\rem [it] Jesus was separated a little while from his disciples by his death, and was with them again a little while after his resurrection.\rem [it]*
\ip 3. What was the proof that satisfied the unbelieving disciples? \rq (Vs. 19, 30)\rq*—\rem [it] Jesus knowing their wish or thought, and telling them plainly that he was going hack to his Father.\rem [it]*
\ip 4. What is our consolation in trouble? \rq (V. 33)\rq*—\rem [it] That Christ has overcome the world, and that in him we may have peace.\rem [it]*
\ms4 John 17.
\ip 1. What " hour " did Jesus refer to in verse 11?—\rem [it] The time of his death upon the cross.\rem [it]*
\ip 2. What is " life eternal "?—\rem [it] To truly know God as our reconciled Father in Jesus Christ. Union with Christ is life eternal already begun.\rem [it]*
\ip 3. Can we at the end of our life use the words of our Lord in verse 4?—\rem [it] No; we all of us fall short of doing the work for God, and so of bringing him the glory that we might.\rem [it]*
\ip 4. Must we not rather use the words of Isa. 53.6?—\rem [it] Yes; we have indeed too much "turned every one to his own way."\rem [it]*
\ip 5. Who was the son of perdition?—\rem [it] Judas, who was fast falling into ruin and perdition.\rem [it]*
\ip 6. How do we know that believers of the present day were included in the Lord's petition? \rq (V. 20)\rq*—\rem [it] Because they believe through the word of the apostles handed down in the New Testament, and through the preaching and teaching of a succession of Christ's people from that day to this.\rem [it]*
\ms4 John 18. 19 (Matthew 26; Mark 14; Luke 22).
\ip 1. Why did the high priest question Jesus as to his disciples?—\rem [it] To know the number and rank of his followers.\rem [it]*
\ip 2. Does not John 18. 28 contain an illustration of the parable of the mote and beam? \rq (Matt. 7. 5)\rq*—\rem [it] Yes; the people shrunk from entering a heathen court, as they thought it would defile them, and so unfit them to eat the Passover; and yet they did not shrink from the far greater guilt of causing Jesus' death.\rem [it]*
\ip 3. Does John 18. 30 show the hollowness of the accusations of the Jews?—\rem [it] Yes, as they did not dare to bring any particular charge against him.\rem [it]*
\ip 4. How did John 18, verses 31 and 32, show in what manner our Lord would be put to death?—\rem [it] The Jews put to death by stoning, but as they were now under Roman government, Jesus would suffer by the Roman form of crucifixion.\rem [it]*
\ip 5. To whom did our Lord appear first after his resurrection? \rq (. 56)\rq*—\rem [it] To Mary Magdalene and Mary the mother of James. Matt. 28. 1. 5: 27\rem [it]*
\ip 6. To whom was his second appearance? \rq (John 20. 11-18)\rq*—\rem [it] To Mary Magdalene.\rem [it]*
\ip 7. To whom was his third appearance? \rq (1 Cor. 15. 5)\rq*—\rem [it] To Peter. \rem [it]*
\ip 8. To whom was Jesus' fourth appearance? \rq (Luke 14. 13)\rq*—\rem [it] To two disciples on the way to Emmaus.\rem [it]*
\ip 9. To whom was the fifth appearance? \rq (1 Cor. 15. 5)\rq*—\rem [it] To an evening assembly of the apostles or disciples. John 20. 19; \rem [it]*
\ip 10. What were the circumstances of the sixth? \rq (John 20. 24)\rq*—\rem [it] Jesus appeared again to the disciples, and made himself especially known to Thomas.\rem [it]*
\ip 11. To whom was the seventh manifestation? \rq (John 21. 1)\rq*—\rem [it] To some of the disciples and to Nathanael at the Sea of Tiberias.\rem [it]*
\ip 12. How many saw the Lord upon his eighth appearance?—\rem [it] The apostles and about five hundred brethren at once.\rem [it]*
\ip 13. Where?—\rem [it] On a mountain in Galilee.\rem [it]*
\ip 14. To whom was our Lord's ninth appearance? \rq (1 Cor. 15. 7)\rq*—\rem [it] To James. \rem [it]*
\ip 15. Who witnessed the final appearance? \rq (Acts 1. 4)\rq*—\rem [it] " All the apostles," by whom he had been "seen forty days." 1 Cor. 15". 7;\rem [it]*
\ip 16. What was our Lord's last act upon earth? \rq (Luke 24. 50, 51)\rq*—\rem [it] To give the disciples his blessing.\rem [it]*
